South African Stocks Advance For Second Day; AngloGold, Conduit Increase

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 
2011-04-14T16:22:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-14/s-african-stocks-bhp-billiton-gold-fields-investec-property.html
The FTSE/JSE  Africa  All Share Index
rose for a second day, adding 64.54, or 0.2 percent, to
32,418.33 at 5 p.m. in Johannesburg.  The following are among the most active stocks in the South
African market today.  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. (ANG)  , Africa’s largest mining
company, increased for a second day, rising 5 rand, or 1.5
percent, to 337 rand. Gold rose for a second straight day on
speculation that higher raw-material costs and record-low
 interest rates  will spur demand for an inflation hedge.  Gold
Fields Ltd. (GFI)  , the third-biggest gold mining company,
added 1.09 rand, or 0.9 percent, to 122.70 rand, a second day of
gains.  Conduit Capital Ltd. (CND)  , an investment holding
Company, rose the most since Nov. 15, adding 5 cents, or 10
percent, to 53 cents. The company expects earnings per share of
4.02 cents in the first-half through February, from 2.78 cents a
year earlier, according to a trading statement it published on
the stock exchange.  Investec Property Fund Ltd. (IPF SJ), a property investment
unit of South African private bank and wealth manager Investec
Plc, began trading at 10.80 rand on the bourse in Johannesburg.
It last traded at 10.40 rand.  Pinnacle Technology Holdings Ltd. (PNC)  , a computer and
networking group, rose the most since April 7, adding 15 cents,
or 2.2 percent, to 6.95 rand. The stock was upgraded to “buy”
from “sell” by Investec Plc analyst Giuseppe Jerman. The price
estimate was raised to 8.37 rand from 6.62 rand.  To contact the reporter on this story:
